<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF8BFFF7FE261A838630B2A2" authority="(White, 1879)" baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[447,868,142,169]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="827" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mulsanti">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF8BFFF7FE261A8387ECB2A2" bold="true" box="[447,696,142,169]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="827">Mesovelia mulsanti</emphasis>
(White, 1879)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF8BFFF7FF591ACE869BB36C" blockId="28.[160,1156,195,359]" pageId="28" pageNumber="827">
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF8BFFF7FF591ACE84C5B2D7" baseAuthorityName="White" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[192,401,195,220]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="827" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mulsanti">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF8BFFF7FF591ACE84C5B2D7" box="[192,401,195,220]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="827">Mesovelia mulsanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported from much of the Caribbean Islands, including 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF8BFFF7FF391AEB8470B2F4" box="[160,292,230,255]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="28" pageNumber="827">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
, St. Thomas, and St. Croix (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF8BFFF7FDC81AEB8699B2F4" author="de Kort-Gommer M &amp; Nieser N" box="[593,973,230,255]" pageId="28" pageNumber="827" pagination="72 - 87" refId="ref24300" refString="de Kort-Gommer M, Nieser N. 1969. Records of Antillean water striders (Heteroptera). Stud Fauna Curacao Carib Isl. 30: 72 - 87." type="journal article" year="1969">de Kort-Gommer and Nieser 1969</bibRefCitation>
). We also found this species on St. Thomas in ghuts, ponds, and mangrove brackish pools and streams. Typically, this species was found where the water was calm, but it also occurred along the margins of swift water, where vegetation or woody debris were present.
</paragraph>
